<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Tribute Page | Ada Lovelace</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <main id="main">
        <header>
            <h1 id="title">Ada Lovelace</h1>
            <p>The world's first computer programmer</p>
        </header>

        <figure id="img-div">
            <img 
                id="image" 
                src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Ada_Lovelace_portrait.jpg" 
                alt="Portrait of Ada Lovelace">
            <figcaption id="img-caption">
                An 1836 portrait of Ada Lovelace by Margaret Carpenter.
            </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section id="tribute-info">
            <h2>Timeline of a Visionary</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>1815</strong> - Born in London to Lord Byron and Anne Isabella Milbanke.</li>
                <li><strong>1833</strong> - Met Charles Babbage, the inventor of the Difference Engine.</li>
                <li><strong>1842</strong> - Translated Luigi Menabrea's memoir on Babbage's newer machine, the Analytical Engine.</li>
                <li><strong>1843</strong> - Published "Notes," containing what is recognized as the first computer algorithm.</li>
                <li><strong>1852</strong> - Died at the age of 36, leaving a legacy that wouldn't be fully realized for a century.</li>
            </ul>
            <blockquote>
                <p>"The Analytical Engine weaves algebraic patterns just as the Jacquard loom weaves flowers and leaves."</p>
                <cite>— Ada Lovelace</cite>
            </blockquote>
        </section>

        <footer>
            <p>To learn more about this remarkable woman, visit her 
                <a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ada_Lovelace" target="_blank">Wikipedia page</a>.
            </p>
        </footer>
    </main>
</body>
</html>







